We have, by definition:

380Equationhodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.1.xml1.3.1.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1         E_r^{pq}         =  \operatorname {Im} (Z_r^{pq} \to  K^{p+q}/B_r^{pq})       \tag{1.3.1.1}       

381Equationhodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2.xml1.3.1.2hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1         = Z_r^{pq}/(B_r^{pq} \cap  Z_r^{pq})       \tag{1.3.1.2}       

382Equationhodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.3hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.3.xml1.3.1.3hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1         =  \operatorname {Ker} (K^{p+q}/B_r^{pq} \to  K^{p+q}/(Z_r^{pq}+B_r^{pq})).       \tag{1.3.1.3}       

We can thus write

383Equationhodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.4hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.4.xml1.3.1.4hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1          \begin {aligned}           B_r^{p \bullet } \cap  Z_r^{p \bullet }           & \coloneqq  (dF^{p-r+1}+F^{p+1})  \cap  (d^{-1}F^{p+r} \cap  F^p)          \\ &= (dF^{p-r+1} \cap  F^p) + (F^{p+1} \cap  d^{-1}F^{p+r})          \end {aligned}       \tag{1.3.1.4}       

since dF^{p-r+1} \subset  d^{-1}F^{p+r} and F^{p+1} \subset  F^p.
